# $archon_name — a Demiurge-minted Archon

Generated by Demiurge's `claude-cli` adapter (ADR 0006). The spec
(`archon.agf.yaml`) is the source of truth; this project only serves it.

## Prerequisite

The **Claude Code CLI** (`claude`) must be on PATH (or set `CLAUDE_CLI_BIN`).
There is no pip package for it — install it per Anthropic's docs and sign in.

## Run

    uv run python server.py --port 9999

The agent card is served at the A2A well-known path
(`/.well-known/agent-card.json`) for discovery; delegation happens over A2A
JSON-RPC at `/`. The server boots and serves its card without the CLI
installed or authenticated.

Delegated tasks execute the spec's `agf.react` policy by shelling out to
`claude -p`. **Billing is the operator's Claude subscription** — the logged-in
`claude` account, or a `CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN` minted once with
`claude setup-token` for unattended service. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is scrubbed
from the CLI's environment on every invocation so a stray key can never switch
the Archon to metered API billing (the deliberate inversion of the claude-sdk
adapter's key passthrough).

The spec's `max_steps` is advisory on this runtime (the CLI exposes no turn
cap); the hard rail is the spec's `constraints.budget.max_duration_seconds`,
enforced as a subprocess timeout (default 600 s when the spec declares none).

## Tool grants

Built-in runtime tools declared in the spec's `action_space.local_tools` are
passed to the CLI as pre-approved `--allowedTools` entries — a local tool's
`name` is a Claude Code tool name or specifier (e.g. `Bash`, `WebSearch`,
`Bash(python *)`), defaulting to its alias.

MCP servers declared in `action_space.mcp_servers` carry portable
`server_ref` identities; mapping those to real connection details is the
runtime owner's job (as the Agent Format spec assigns it). To wire them up:

1. Copy `mcp-servers.example.json` (generated when the spec declares grants)
   to `mcp-servers.json`.
2. Replace each entry with the real connection config for that server —
   e.g. `{"command": "npx", "args": ["-y", "some-mcp-server"], "env": {}}` or
   `{"type": "http", "url": "https://..."}`.

At boot, `server.py` renders the mapped servers into `cli-mcp-config.json`
(the CLI's `--mcp-config` shape) and passes `--strict-mcp-config` so the
Archon sees exactly its granted servers and nothing else the operator's
machine has configured. Allowed tools follow the spec (`mcp__<alias>__<tool>`;
a grant without `allowed_tools` allows the whole server). Grants with no entry
in `mcp-servers.json` are skipped — the Archon runs without them. Keep
`mcp-servers.json` out of version control if it holds secrets.
